## Highlights {.unnumbered}

- We define the greatest lower bound (also called the infimum) of a set and prove that these exist in $\R$ whenever a nonempty subset is bounded below.
- We prove the Nested Interval Theorem, which shows that the intersection of a nested sequence of closed intervals is nonempty.
- We show how the Nested Interval Theorem can be used to prove that $\R$ is uncountable.

## Preparation {.unnumbered}

We start with a definition that should seem very natural given what we did in the last section.

:::{.definition #def-inf}
Let $S\subseteq\R$ be a subset of the real numbers.

1. We say $b\in\R$ is a *lower bound* of $S$ if for all $x\in S$, $b\leq x.$ If $S$ has a lower bound, we say $S$ is *bounded below*.
2. We say that $l\in\R$ the *greatest lower bound* or *infimum* of $S$ if for all lower bounds $b$ of $S$, $l\geq b$, and in this case we write 
$$l=\inf S.$$

3. If $l$ is the greatest lower bound $S$ and $l\in S$, we say that $l$ is the *least element* of $S.$
:::

:::{.exercise #exr-inf-examples}
Find the infimum and least element of each set below or say why it doesn't have one.

1. $[0,\infty)$
2. $(-\infty,0]$
3. $(0,3]$
4. The set of upper bounds on $[0,3]$.
5. The set of upper bounds on $[0,3)$.
:::

Parts 4 and 5 of @exr-inf-examples are meant to demonstrate another way of thinking about the Least Upper Bound Axiom: it tells us that sets of upper bounds *always* have a least element when they are non-empty.

Rather than make an assumption about infima existing, as we did with suprema, we can prove this as a theorem from the Least Upper Bound Axiom using this idea.

:::{.theorem #thm-infs-exist .lub-thread}
If a nonempty subset $S\subseteq\R$ has a lower bound, then $S$ has a greatest lower bound in $\R$.
:::

:::{.proof}
Suppose $S\subseteq\R$ is nonempty and bounded below. Then let $T$ be the *set of lower bounds* of $S$. Note that $T$ is nonempty (since $S$ was bounded above) and bounded above (by any element of $S$). Thus $T$ has a least upper bound $l=\sup T$.

I claim that $l=\inf(S)$. First, we note that $l$ is in fact greater than any other lower bound of $S$, since $l$ is an upper bound on $T$. Also, since every element of $S$ is an upper bound on $T$, we have $l\leq s$ for all $s\in S$ since $l$ is the *least* upper bound of $T$.
:::

:::{.exercise #exr-infs-exist-2}
Try proving @thm-infs-exist another way. Consider the set $U=\{x\st -x\in S\}$, and show that $-\sup U=\inf S$.^[We will use this kind of technqiue frequently to obtain the second two cases of a theorem we want to prove (e.g. one for increasing functions and one for decreasing function, or one for sups and one for infs).]
:::

One more concept we'll need in order to get started on this section is the idea of taking an infinite union or intersection, which will be important for understanding the Nested Interval Theorem. 

